{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load the four CSV files metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory and keep them in kernel variables for subsequent steps. For each file, return a compact summary only (no full tables):
1) total row count;
2) minimum timestamp and maximum timestamp (as integers);
3) list of unique cmdb_id values (limit to first 50, sorted alphabetically);
4) list of unique KPI/trace/log name values (for metric->kpi_name, trace->trace_name, log->log_name; limit to first 50, sorted alphabetically). If a file has no such field, return an empty list;
5) top 5 rows (show these columns only: timestamp, cmdb_id, kpi_name/trace_name/log_name/message/value as applicable) to verify formats.
Return the results as a JSON-serializable dictionary mapping each filename to its summary. Keep outputs concise and do not print full raw time series. Cache loaded dataframes in kernel variables for next steps." }

{
    "analysis": "Loaded telemetry files into kernel variables (metric_df, trace_df, log_df, error_logs_df). Files cover timestamps that include the incident window: metric.csv spans 1647792000–1647795600 and trace/log cover parts of that range. No error_logs entries. Next we must follow preprocessing: compute global thresholds for each component-KPI (using full available series) before filtering to the incident window. These thresholds will be used to detect anomalies inside March 21, 2022 00:30–01:00 (UTC+8).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the cached metric_df in the kernel, aggregate statistics per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available metric series (do NOT filter by incident time yet). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: count, min, max, mean, std, global P95 (95th percentile), and global P5 (5th percentile). Store the aggregated result in a kernel variable named component_kpi_stats (with one row per cmdb_id-kpi_name and the computed stats).
Return a compact JSON-serializable summary containing only: 
1) total number of unique cmdb_id-kpi_name pairs;
2) top 20 pairs sorted by count (descending) with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min, max, mean, std, p95, p5;
3) the number of pairs where max > p95 * 1.5 (indicating large high-side deviations) and number where min < p5 * 0.5 (large low-side deviations).
Limit returned rows to at most 20. Cache component_kpi_stats for the next step." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global statistics (count, min, max, mean, std, p95, p5) for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair using the full metric series and cached the result as component_kpi_stats. There are 5,282 pairs; several pairs (257) show large high-side deviations and many (296) large low-side deviations across their full histories. Next we must detect anomalies inside the incident window (March 21, 2022 00:30–01:00 UTC+8) by comparing metric points in that window to the precomputed global thresholds (p95 and p5). The goal is to narrow candidate component-KPI pairs and components for deeper trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter metric_df to the incident window: March 21, 2022 00:30:00 to 2022-03-21 01:00:00 in UTC+8. Join each metric row with component_kpi_stats on (cmdb_id, kpi_name) to obtain p95 and p5. Flag a row as an anomaly if value >= p95 OR value <= p5. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that has at least one anomaly in the window compute these aggregates: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, max_over_p95 (max_value_in_window / p95 if p95>0 else null), min_over_p5 (min_value_in_window / p5 if p5>0 else null), and a severity score defined as max( (max_over_p95 - 1) if max_over_p95>1 else 0, (1 - min_over_p5) if min_over_p5<1 else 0 ).
Return a JSON-serializable summary containing:
1) total number of metric rows in the incident window;
2) total number of distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs with anomalies in the window;
3) number of distinct cmdb_id components affected;
4) top 30 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs sorted by severity desc with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, severity. Limit rows to 30.
Cache the per-pair anomaly table in kernel variable named window_anomalies for follow-up steps." }

{
    "analysis": "We have aggregated global thresholds for all component-KPI pairs and detected anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-21 00:30–01:00 UTC+8). The window shows very widespread anomalies (5,190 pairs) affecting 59 components. The highest-severity signals include node-level I/O and iowait metrics (node-1, node-3, node-5) and many container-level network receive spikes on eth0 across many service pods (paymentservice, shippingservice, recommendationservice, emailservice, checkoutservice, etc.). These observations suggest two dominant patterns to inspect as candidate root causes: (1) node disk I/O / iowait spikes, and (2) elevated inbound network traffic on pod eth0 interfaces. To progress from anomaly detection to fault identification, we must convert per-point anomalies into consecutive fault intervals and filter out isolated/nonsignificant spikes so we can compare candidate faults by start time and severity.\n\nWhat I will ask next: identify consecutive anomaly runs (faults) for the highest-severity (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs discovered in window_anomalies, summarize each fault (start, end, length, max/min in window, associated p95/p5, computed severity), and filter out trivial single-point non-severe spikes. This will let us see which fault(s) start earliest and have the largest deviation, helping decide the root cause level (node vs container) and exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached window_anomalies table, take the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs by severity. For each pair, retrieve the original metric_df rows restricted to the incident window and ordered by timestamp. Mark each row as 'anomaly' when value >= p95 OR value <= p5 (use p95/p5 from component_kpi_stats joined earlier). Identify consecutive anomaly runs where successive timestamps differ by <=60 seconds. For every run (fault) produce one summary row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp (earliest timestamp in run), fault_end_timestamp (latest timestamp in run), length_in_points, max_value_in_run, min_value_in_run, p95, p5, run_max_over_p95 (max_value_in_run/p95 if p95>0 else null), run_min_over_p5 (min_value_in_run/p5 if p5>0 else null), and run_severity defined as max( (run_max_over_p95 - 1) if >0 else 0, (1 - run_min_over_p5) if <1 else 0 ).\nFilter out runs that are single-point (length_in_points == 1) and where run_max_over_p95 <= 1.5 and run_min_over_p5 >= 0.66 (i.e., low-impact isolated spikes). Return a JSON-serializable list of up to 20 fault summary rows sorted by run_severity descending. Also return the earliest fault_start_timestamp among all returned runs. Cache the resulting fault table in kernel variable named window_faults." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-level preprocessing, global threshold calculation, anomaly detection in the incident window, and conversion of anomalies into consecutive fault runs (window_faults). The window shows widespread anomalies across many components. The highest run_severity items include node-level I/O/iowait faults (node-1, node-5, node-3) and many container-level network receive spikes (kpi_name containing container.node-6.*) across many pods. The earliest detected fault_start_timestamp among the reported runs is 1647793800 (the start of the incident window). To localize the root cause we must (A) inspect the node-level faults (their timings and severities) and (B) quantify how many pod/container faults map to each physical node (by parsing node id from container.* kpi_name) so we can identify which node(s) host the most impacted pods. According to the root-cause rules, if multiple node faults exist we should pick the predominant node(s) with most faults or the node-level fault with the largest deviation. We need compact aggregates to compare node-level severities vs. pod-impact counts to decide the root cause node and the exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached window_faults and window_anomalies (and metric_df if needed) perform two compact analyses:\n1) Node-level faults: filter window_faults rows where cmdb_id starts with 'node-'. Return up to 20 rows sorted by run_severity desc with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp, fault_end_timestamp, length_in_points, max_value_in_run, p95, run_max_over_p95, run_severity. Also return the earliest fault_start_timestamp among these node-level faults.\n2) Pod-impact by physical node: from window_faults (all faults) find fault runs whose kpi_name contains the substring 'container.node-<N>.' (pattern 'container.node-' followed by node id then a dot). Extract the node token (e.g., 'node-6') from kpi_name for each run where cmdb_id does NOT start with 'node-'. For each extracted node compute: node_id, number_of_pod_fault_runs (count of runs mapped to this node), distinct_pods_affected (count of unique cmdb_id values mapped), earliest_pod_fault_start (min fault_start_timestamp). Return the top 20 nodes sorted by number_of_pod_fault_runs desc. \nReturn results as a JSON object with two fields: 'node_faults' (list from step 1) and 'node_pod_impact' (list from step 2). Keep outputs bounded to the requested columns and row limits and cache any new tables in the kernel for next steps." }

{
    "analysis": "The last query checked whether the node-1 host-level anomalies (high iowait / I/O waits) had corresponding anomalous container metrics that embed 'container.node-1.' and found none. Interpretation: node-1 exhibits strong host-level resource anomalies in metric-based faults, but we do not see pod-level anomalies encoded with the 'container.node-1.' KPI pattern in the incident window. Meanwhile, earlier analysis showed a concentrated cluster of pod-level container.network_receive spikes mapped to node-6 (12 fault runs, 11 pods) starting at the incident window start (1647793800). According to the localization rules, we must now use traces and logs to (A) confirm which level (node vs pod) best explains the observed service degradations and (B) identify the most downstream faulty component if multiple same-level faults exist.

What we still need to resolve: whether the single-host, high-severity node-1 faults are the root cause despite lacking container-level anomalies (possible if node-1 hosted critical services), or whether the widespread pod network spikes tied to node-6 better explain service-level failures. Traces (latency/error rates between services) will help locate whether request latency/error propagation begins at node-6-hosted pods or correlates with node-1 timing. Therefore we should perform trace analysis next to find trace features (duration_p95/duration_mean/error_rate) that are anomalous in the incident window, identify which service/pod traces degrade first, and compare their earliest anomaly times with node-1/node-5/node-6 timings.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute global statistics for traces using the full trace_df (do NOT filter by incident window first). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: count, min, max, mean, std, global P95, global P5 and cache as component_trace_stats.
Then filter trace_df to the incident window (timestamps between 1647793800 and 1647795600 inclusive). Join with component_trace_stats to get p95/p5. Flag an anomaly if: value >= p95 (for duration and error_rate signals) OR value <= p5 (for success-rate-style signals if any). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) with ≥1 anomaly in the window compute: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, p95, p5, max_over_p95 (if p95>0), and severity = (max_over_p95 - 1) if max_over_p95>1 else 0.
Return a compact JSON object with: 
1) total trace rows in the window;
2) total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs with anomalies in window;
3) distinct components (cmdb_id) affected by trace anomalies;
4) top 20 anomalous (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs sorted by severity desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95, severity.
Cache component_trace_stats and the per-pair anomaly summary as kernel variables for follow-up steps." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the full workflow: computed global thresholds, detected metric anomalies in the incident window, identified consecutive fault runs, and used traces and logs to narrow candidates. Key findings: (1) many pod-level container.network_receive spikes and elevated trace error_rate/duration anomalies are concentrated on node-6 with earliest anomalies at 1647793800 (2022-03-21 00:30:00 UTC+8); (2) node-1 and node-5 show very large host-level I/O/iowait faults, but node-1 lacks mapped container anomalies and node-5 I/O runs start later (1647795240); (3) node-6 pods show significant trace error anomalies with no corresponding application log.error_count increases, consistent with an infra/network issue on node-6 causing RPC errors/latency. These lines of evidence make node-6 the leading root-cause candidate, but we still need to confirm host-level network anomalies on node-6 (host NIC or network metrics) to tie pod-level container spikes to a node-level network cause.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached metric_df and component_kpi_stats, filter metric_df to cmdb_id == 'node-6' and the incident window timestamps 1647793800 through 1647795600. Join each row to component_kpi_stats to obtain the global p95 and p5. Flag rows as anomalies when value >= p95 OR value <= p5. Aggregate anomalies by kpi_name and compute: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95, p5, max_over_p95 (if p95>0), and severity = max_over_p95 - 1 (or 0 if <=0). Return a JSON list of up to top 20 node-6 host kpi_name rows sorted by severity desc with the requested columns. Cache the result as node6_host_anomalies for follow-up steps." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds, detected metric anomalies in the incident window, identified consecutive fault runs, and used traces/logs to narrow candidates. Findings so far: (1) widespread container.network_receive spikes and elevated trace error_rate/duration anomalies concentrate on pods colocated on node-6 with earliest anomalies at 1647793800; (2) node-1 and node-5 present larger host-level I/O/iowait faults, but node-1 lacks mapped container anomalies and node-5 faults start later; (3) node-6 host metrics show only mild anomalies (system.io.w_s and small net changes), yet many node-6 pods have large container-level network receive spikes and many trace error_rate anomalies while application logs show no error_count increases. Temporal alignment: node-6 pod anomalies start at 1647793800 and trace errors appear soon after (e.g., 1647794220), supporting node-6 as the likely infrastructure-level source of RPC failures.\n\nWhat remains: we need direct network-failure evidence on node-6 (packet errors, drops, retransmits) at container or host level to justify assigning the root-cause reason to a network problem (e.g., packet loss/retransmission/latency). Host-level node-6 KPIs show only modest deviations; the decisive evidence would be container/network error KPIs (container_network_*errors*, packet drops, retransmits) for node-6. Confirming such signals will let us conclude node-6 as the root-cause component and pick the earliest anomalous timestamp on node-6 (1647793800) as the root cause occurrence time and assign a network-related reason. Until we verify those network-error KPIs, final attribution would be premature.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From cached metric_df and component_kpi_stats, find all KPIs where kpi_name contains the substring 'container.node-6.container_network' (match any network-related container KPI on node-6). For each such KPI compute aggregated anomaly info restricted to the incident window (1647793800–1647795600): anomaly_count (value>=p95 or value<=p5 as earlier), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95, max_over_p95 (null if p95==0), and severity = max_over_p95 - 1 (or 0 if <=0). Return a JSON list of up to 20 rows sorted by severity desc with these columns: kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, latest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95, max_over_p95, severity. Cache the result as node6_container_net_anomalies." }

